commitResults.messageBody:
Task class does not have any methods to retrieve dates from child
classes.

Storage Class needs the date attribute in child classes like Deadline
and Event for the saving and loading tasks correctly.

Modify Task to be an abstract class with an abstract method getDates().
getDates() can be defined in the respective child classes to return the
number of dates required for the class.

Using abstract methods in this case is preferable as to not introduce
unnecessary methods in classes that do not need them. Each child
class returns different number of dates, and this approach ensures
flexibility.

commitResults.messageBody:
Tasks cannot be compared meaningfully.

With LocalDateTime being used instead of Strings, it is essential to
have a consistent way of comparing Tasks.

A new abstract method compareDate() will return the date which we can
use to compare the task. TaskComparator will rank Tasks based on that
date.

This method will ensure consistency as there are tasks having multiple
dates associated with them and some having none.

commitResults.messageBody:
All the commands and functionalities are executed through switch-case
statement in Main.

The Main function is cluttered and as more commands are introduced
it will get longer.

An abstract class Command is defined and all commands will be subclasses
of Command. Functionalities of each command will be encapsulated in
its class.

This approach allows new commands to be added in easily without
cluttering the Main class.

commitResults.messageBody:
The logic for parsing, displaying messages to user as well as executing
commands are found in Ella.

Ella is very long and cluttered and does multiple tasks.

Separate the various components into various classes. Ui handles
user input related tasks, Parser will parse the user input and Command
will execute the functionalities of a given command.

This ensures code will be more organized as well as easier to read.

commitResults.messageBody:
There are no assert statements checking assumptions which should hold
true.

There may be bugs introduced due to underlying assumption.

Assert statements are used to validate assumption as they are a good
way to catch inconsistencies.
